<font color="#FF0000">A SOLDIER'S DUTY</font><br>
<tt>Sun Sep 21 11:08:38 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Mustang Two Four<br>
I don't know if or not I have PTSD, if I do I get a lower interest rate on my VA loan. Finally used the VA benefits, I could have gotten a cheaper loan rate going conventional. <br><br>
MTF, Looks like you've been doing some good book learning. If you'll like we can swap psychological books back and forth. Sorry, only have about 22 books on the subject and most of them are from a Christian perspective. Personally, I think all those low bidders for the government contract to provide psychologist like spatz to treat NV  PTSD veterans are a bunch of greedy, self-serving, mal-adjusted, guilt ridden, half-baked idiots.<br><br>
I never listen to anything spatz has to say. The good the bad or the ugly. It's not like I believe that there are communist behind every rock, it's just that I want to know why the commie placed the rock there in the first place. Why does spatz respond the way he does? Others have asked him to come clean and he runs and hides and instead wants to begin treatment. Listening to what spatz has to say about VN vets is like trying to convince me you've trained your cat to go out and get your slippers. It isn't going to happen.<br>
Take a look above on the one hand spatz a war protestor/resister, who calls vets murderers, now wants to be the corpsmen for what he calls the hyena pack. Getting psychoanalysis by spatz for PTSD is like having Ronnie King hold the taser gun while the city burns in the background and he tells us, it's wasn't my fault and &quot;Can't we all get along.&quot; It just does not make sense to me. <br>
We've created a lot of casualties since the war because of individuals like spatz.<br>
It seems like North Vietnam soldiers suffered little psychological scars from their war experiences according to today's LA Times. Maybe we can send them some of our psychologist and see how many of them they can turn into victims of their distorted views of what PTSD is.<br><br>
I can not dismiss what Chet has said lightly; there is much wisdom in what he has stated. The beginning of his response said, <br>
&quot;I learned, for me, that it had nothing to do with what I did in country. It was how I internalized it.&quot; <br>
That maybe the key often overlooked. A lot of how we viewed the war and our particular involvement in it has to do with how we internalized what we saw, felt, and did, coupled with how and what type of reception we had in our homecoming. A lot of it can be traced directly to the guilt trip laid on us for having done our duty as soldiers in an undeclared war with changing rules and regulations. It was still war and you kill people in war, men women and children. I don't know if I ever killed any innocent women or children. If they crossed the path of my Machine gun or behind a hooch I was firing into, I probably did, but it was war and I don't regret doing my duty, such are the causalities of war. Damn if you do, and damn if you don't.<br><br>
The welcome home, &quot;The conquering hero&quot; unlike other wars was replaced with condemnation, by peolpe like spatz. <br>
I would venture to believe that many of those that served prior to the time of mass demonstrations, media distortion and condemnation did not suffer PTSD in as heavy or as destructive force as those who came after them. Now, that is my opinion at this time but I have not taken the time or seen anything to substantiate it. <br><br>
The only clear evidence that I can personally refer to is found in our company's makeup. There were 47 Marines in our platoon when I first arrived in Nam, given the many that came in and out, either by rotating, getting wounded or killed there were only a handful of us that came out of it without getting seriously wounded. Of the Marines I have been able to contact 32 now, only two that I know of have a PTSD problem and they both were captured and dragged away by the enemy until we went and got them back.   Of the over 300 Marines in our Company's roster and I have spoken to the greater number of them, only a handful suffers from PTSD to any noticeable degree. Most have jobs, are married and have gone on with their lives, suffering only the same experiences as any other individual in their age group that served or did not serve in Nam. I don't really know what that means at this point except that there is something there. The majority, 80-90 percent remained silent about their involvement in the war and clearly all but 4-7 had any negative feelings about having served or having been betrayed by their government.<br><br>
One of the most deceiving ploys employed by so-called government paid psychologist is to get you to a point of admitting you did something wrong (IN WAR?) like killed the enemy or civilians during engagement then they get you to admit that the war was wrong and to blame it on shadowly government officials. Transferred anger, but it still eats away at you. Because when you care about your country the flip-flopping even if your country's wrong causes pain and misunderstanding because the guilt still remains and we realize we are the government and responsible for those in higher position of authority. <br>
American Vietnam Veterans, need to be regogzined for the good we accomplished while we served under the worst of conditions and lack of support. I end the introduction to my book with these words, <br>
&quot;We will never see battles again as we did in Viet Nam. If we failed, it was not because we did not do our duty, it was because others entrusted with higher responsibilities failed to do theirs.&quot;<br><br>
In today's LA Times one of the NVA soldiers in a rehabilitation hospital for NVA vets and who have received honor and respect from their fellow countrymen said this. <br>
     &quot;For our children, what I want is that there is never another war,&quot; said Pham Cong Lien, 50, who was wounded in a B-52 strike in 1971. &quot;We have paid so greatly for our independence, but we all know that war is made by much higher authorities than us. We are here because we did a soldier's duty.&quot; <br>

<p><code>-- USA, USMC, India Comapny 3/7, Machine Gunner  (Sparrowhawk) </code><p>


